# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: debian-linux
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] APT is a collection of tools distributed in a package named *apt*.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] A significant part of APT is defined in a C++ library of functions; APT also includes command-line programs for dealing with packages, which use the library.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] Three such programs are `apt`, `apt-get` and `apt-cache`.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] They are commonly used in examples because they are simple and ubiquitous.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] The *apt* package is of "*important*" priority in all current Debian releases, and is therefore included in a default Debian installation.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] APT can be considered a front end to `dpkg`, friendlier than the older `dselect` front end.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] While `dpkg` performs actions on individual packages, APT manages relations (especially dependencies) between them, as well as sourcing and management of higher-level versioning decisions such as release tracking and Upgrade Suppression.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] APT is often hailed as one of Debian's best features, which Debian developers attribute to the strict quality controls in Debian's policy.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] A major feature of APT is the way it calls `dpkg` –it performs topological sorting of the list of packages to be installed or removed and calls `dpkg` in the best possible sequence.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] In some cases, it utilizes the `--force` options of `dpkg`.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] However, it only does this when it is unable to calculate how to avoid the reason `dpkg` requires the action to be forced.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] The user indicates one or more packages to be installed.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] Each package name is phrased as just the name portion of the package, not a fully qualified filename (for instance, in a Debian system, `libc6` would be the argument provided, not `libc6_1.9.6-2.deb`).
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] Notably, APT automatically gets and installs packages upon which the indicated package depends (if necessary).
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] This was an original distinguishing characteristic of APT-based package management systems, as it avoided installation failure due to missing dependencies, a type of dependency hell.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] Another distinction is the retrieval of packages from remote repositories.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] APT uses a location configuration file (`/etc/apt/sources.list`) to locate the desired packages, which might be available on the network or a removable storage medium, for example, and retrieve them, and also obtain information about available (but not installed) packages.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] APT provides other command options to override decisions made by apt-get's conflict resolution system.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] One option is to force a particular version of a package.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] This can downgrade a package and render dependent software inoperable, so the user must be careful.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] Finally, the `apt_preferences` mechanism allows the user to create an alternative installation policy for individual packages.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] The user can specify packages using a POSIX regular expression.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] APT searches its cached list of packages and lists the dependencies that must be installed or updated.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] APT retrieves, configures and installs the dependencies automatically.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] Triggers are the treatment of deferred actions.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] `/etc/apt` contains the APT configuration folders and files.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] `apt-config` is the APT Configuration Query program.
[src:debian-linux/apt-software] `apt-config dump` shows the configuration.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Debian packages are standard Unix ar archives that include two tar archives.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] One archive holds the control information and another contains the installable data.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] dpkg provides the basic functionality for installing and manipulating Debian packages.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Generally end users don't manage packages directly with dpkg but instead use the APT package management software or other APT front-ends such as aptitude (nCurses) and synaptic (GTK).
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Debian packages can be converted into other package formats and vice versa using alien, and created from source code using checkinstall or the Debian Package Maker.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Some core Debian packages are available as **udeb**s ("micro debs"), and are typically used only for bootstrapping a Debian installation.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Although these files use the *udeb* filename extension, they adhere to the same structure specification as ordinary *deb* files.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] However, unlike their *deb* counterparts, *udeb* packages contain only essential functional files.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] In particular, documentation files are normally omitted.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] *udeb* packages are not installable on a standard Debian system, but are used in Debian-Installer.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Prior to Debian 0.93, a package consisted of a file header and two concatenated gzip archives.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Since Debian 0.93, a deb package is implemented as an ar archive.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] **control archive** - A tar archive named `control.tar` contains the maintainer scripts and the package meta-information (package name, version, dependencies and maintainer).
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Compressing the archive with gzip or xz and zstd is supported.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] The file extension changes to indicate the compression method.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] **data archive** - A tar archive named `data.tar` contains the actual installable files.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Compressing the archive with gzip, bzip2, lzma or xz and zstd is supported.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Debian-based distributions support OpenPGP signature verification of signed Debian packages, but most (if not all) have this feature disabled by default.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Instead packages are verified by signing the repository metadata (i.e.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] The metadata files in turn include checksums for the repository files as a means to verify authenticity of the files.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Currently there are two different implementations for signing individual packages.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] The first is done via the debsigs / debsig-verify toolset, which is supported by dpkg.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] The second is done through the dpkg-sig program which is not supported by dpkg, so the packages have to be manually checked with the dpkg-sig program.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Both formats add new sections to the ar archive to store the signature information, but the formats are not compatible with one another.
[src:debian-linux/deb-file-format] Neither of the modifications to the package format are listed in the official Debian handbook or man page about the binary package format.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] It is deployed across servers, personal computers, and embedded devices.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Among Linux distributions, it ranks second only to Ubuntu (which is itself derived from Debian), with 16% of the overall market.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] According to the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 11.4% of developers use it as their primary personal operating system and 10.4% professionally.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Its emphasis on stability and long-term support over frequent package updates has made it prevalent in server and embedded deployments.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Development is led by the Project Leader and guided by two foundational documents: the Debian Social Contract, a summary of the project's commitments that includes the Debian Free Software Guidelines (DFSG), and the Debian Constitution, which describes the organizational structure.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The project publishes three concurrent development branches: stable, testing, and unstable, which correspond to different levels of software maturity.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The current stable release, "Trixie", released on August 9, 2025, includes tens of thousands of packages maintained by more than a thousand active contributors.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Since 1997, the project has operated independently through Software in the Public Interest (SPI), a non-profit corporation founded by project members to hold its assets and trademarks.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] It previously received support from the Free Software Foundation (FSF) between 1994 and 1995, a sponsorship that ended due to disagreements.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian uses version numbers and code names based on the characters of the *Toy Story* franchise to refer to its releases.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] This naming convention was introduced by former project leader Bruce Perens, who was working at Pixar at the time.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The unstable branch is permanently named after Sid, the neighborhood child known for destroying toys.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The first public mention of the project occurred on August 16, 1993, when Ian Murdock posted an announcement to the *comp.os.linux.development* newsgroup.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Murdock founded the project due to his dissatisfaction with the Softlanding Linux System (SLS); after making extensive modifications to this system, he concluded that it would be more efficient to develop a new distribution from scratch.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Similar to the original announcement of Linux, Murdock's post solicited feedback and suggestions on how the system could be improved.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The name *Debian* was a portmanteau of his first name and that of his then-wife, Deborah Lynn.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The first internal release, pre-alpha 0.01, came out on September 15, 1993.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The first public versions, beta 0.90 and beta 0.91, followed on January 26 and 29, 1994, respectively, with their mailing lists hosted by Pixar.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] These releases included the Debian Linux Manifesto, in which Murdock outlined his vision for the project, advocating for a distribution "developed openly in the spirit of Linux and GNU".
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Between November 1994 and November 1995, the project was sponsored by the FSF, whose sponsorship Murdock had sought with the hope that it would also give the FSF experience in packaging a complete GNU system.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] In March 1995, Murdock stepped down as project leader to dedicate more time to his studies, work, and family; the new team did not seek to continue the FSF sponsorship.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Following the end of that sponsorship, Debian motivated the formation of Software in the Public Interest (SPI), a non-profit corporation registered in the state of New York.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] SPI was founded to help Debian and other similar organizations develop and distribute open hardware and software, acting as a fiscal sponsor by handling non-technical administrative tasks so that projects are not required to operate their own legal entity.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] In April 1996, Bruce Perens became the project leader.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] On June 17 of the same year, Debian 1.1 "Buzz" was released, the first release under his leadership.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] By that time, Ian Jackson's dpkg had already become an integral part of Debian.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] He created BusyBox to enable running the installer from a single floppy disk.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] By the time Debian 1.2 "Rex" was released on December 12, 1996, the project had grown to nearly 200 volunteers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Perens stepped down as project leader in December 1997 and left the project entirely on March 18, 1998.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Ian Jackson became project leader in January 1998.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 2.0 "Hamm", released on July 24, 1998, was the first multi-architecture release of Debian, adding support for the Motorola 68000 family (m68k).
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] On December 2, 1998, the Debian Constitution was ratified for the first time, simultaneously initiating the election process that would result in Wichert Akkerman succeeding Jackson as project leader in January 1999.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] On March 9, 1999, Debian 2.1 "Slink" was released, alongside the package manager front-end APT.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] On May 23, 1999, the Internal Revenue Service determined that SPI qualifies for 501(c)(3) status, providing a mechanism by which the Debian Project may accept contributions that are tax deductible in the United States.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] On December 13, 2000, Debian activated package pools on its ftp-master archive server, a change to the archive system that had to be made before preparation of the "Woody" release could begin.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] A package pool consists of a collection of different versions of a given package, from which branches, experimental, unstable, testing, and stable, draw packages for inclusion in their respective package files.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] This change enabled special-purpose distributions, including a new testing branch that was used for the first time to prepare "Woody" for release.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Under this system, packages from unstable considered to be sufficiently stable were promoted to testing after a waiting period of several weeks, a mechanism intended to reduce freeze time and allow the project to prepare a new release at any point.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The first Debian Conference was held in Bordeaux, France, from July 5 to 9, 2000.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The event brought Debian developers and advanced users together in person for the first time, giving the Debian project a physical presence as an organization rather than existing solely as an online collective.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] In addition to working sessions, the conference served as a venue for attendees to meet other members of the free software community, with some presentations open to the general public.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The program combined presentations, technical talks, birds-of-a-feather sessions, and coding parties.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] In May 2001, Hewlett-Packard (HP) announced that it would use Debian as the basis for its future Linux development work.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian developer Bruce Perens, who acted as HP's Linux advocate, disclosed the decision in an email to the Debian development mailing list, noting that HP had already begun distributing Debian to customers and planned to offer support and training for it.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Perens described the move as an initial step toward HP's broader support for the Linux Standard Base (LSB) project.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] On November 20, 2002, a fire destroyed the network operations center at the University of Twente in the Netherlands, which hosted one of Debian's servers, satie.debian.org.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The blaze broke out around 8:00 a.m. local time and consumed the building so thoroughly that firefighters could not save the server room.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Because satie had hosted the project's security archive, its non-US archive, and the databases supporting new-maintainer applications and quality assurance, the corresponding services (security.debian.org, non-us.debian.org, nm.debian.org, and qa.debian.org) went offline as a result.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian subsequently rebuilt these services on another host, klecker, which had recently been relocated from the United States to the Netherlands.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Released on July 19, 2002, Debian 3.0 "Woody" expanded the project's scope.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Supported by a community of over 900 developers and led by newly appointed Project Leader Bdale Garbee, the release included approximately 8,500 binary packages distributed across seven official binary CDs.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] This version broadened hardware compatibility by introducing support for several new architectures, including IA-64, HP PA-RISC, MIPS (both big and little endian), and S/390.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Furthermore, it was the first Debian release to incorporate cryptographic software, following the relaxation of Cold War US cryptography export restrictions, as well as the first to feature the KDE desktop environment after its Qt licensing issues were resolved.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] On October 20, 2004, Mark Shuttleworth announced the first release of Ubuntu, 4.10 "Warty Warthog", a new Debian-derived distribution aimed at combining Debian's extensive package base with a faster installer, a fixed six-month release cycle, and 18 months of security support per release.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The rapid growth of Ubuntu sparked debate within the Debian community regarding the long-term compatibility of Debian-derived distributions.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Some Debian developers warned that as more developers began building packages targeting Ubuntu rather than Debian proper, divergence between the two could erode that compatibility, mimicking the fragmentation seen among RPM-based distributions.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Other community members argued that Debian should address its lengthy release cycles, calling for a predictable, time-based release schedule similar to that adopted by the GNOME Project, in order to reduce the incentive for downstream distributions to fork.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The 3.1 Sarge release was made in June 2005.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] This release updated 73% of the software and included over 9,000 new packages.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] An installation manual and release notes were in ten and fifteen languages respectively.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The efforts of Skolelinux, Debian-Med and Debian-Accessibility raised the number of packages that were educational or had a medical affiliation, and of packages made for people with disabilities.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] In 2006, as a result of a much-publicized dispute, Mozilla software was rebranded in Debian.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The Mozilla Corporation stated that software with unapproved modifications could not be distributed under the Firefox trademark.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Two reasons that Debian had modified the Firefox software were to replace non-free artwork and to provide security patches.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Consequently, Debian contained a fork of Firefox named Iceweasel and one of Thunderbird named Icedove.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] In February 2016, it was announced that Mozilla and Debian had reached an agreement and Iceweasel would revert to the name Firefox; a similar agreement was anticipated for Icedove/Thunderbird.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] A fundraising experiment, Dunc-Tank, was created to solve the release cycle problem and release managers were paid to work full-time; in response, unpaid developers slowed down their work and the release was delayed.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 4.0 (Etch) was released in April 2007, featuring the x86-64 port and a graphical installer.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 5.0 (Lenny) was released in February 2009, supporting Marvell's Orion platform and netbooks such as the Asus Eee PC.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The release was dedicated to Thiemo Seufer, a developer who died in a car crash.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] In July 2009, the policy of time-based development freezes on a two-year cycle was announced.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Time-based freezes are intended to blend the predictability of time based releases with Debian's policy of feature-based releases, and to reduce overall freeze time.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The Squeeze cycle was going to be especially short; however, this initial schedule was abandoned.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] In September 2010, the backporting service became official, providing more recent versions of some software for the stable release.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 6.0 (Squeeze) was released in February 2011, featuring Debian GNU/kFreeBSD as a technology preview, along with adding a dependency-based boot system, and moving problematic firmware to the non-free section.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 7 (Wheezy) was released in May 2013, featuring multiarch support.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 8 (Jessie) was released in April 2015, using systemd as the new init system.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 9 (Stretch) was released in June 2017, with nftables as a replacement for iptables, support for Flatpak apps, and MariaDB as the replacement for MySQL.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian was formerly released as a very large set of CDs for each architecture, but with the release of Debian 9 (Stretch) in 2017, many of the images have been dropped from the archive but remain buildable via jigdo.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 10 (Buster) was released in July 2019, adding support for Secure Boot and enabling AppArmor by default.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 11 (Bullseye) was released in August 2021, enabling persistency in the system journal, adding support for driverless scanning, and containing kernel-level support for exFAT filesystems.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 12 (Bookworm) was released on June 10, 2023, including various improvements and features, increasing the supported Linux kernel to version 6.1, and leveraging new "Emerald" artwork.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 12 also was the first version under a revised Debian Social Contract that includes non-free firmware in its installation media by default, if and when the installer detects that it is needed for installed hardware to function, such as with Wi-Fi cards.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 13 (Trixie) was released on August 9, 2025.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 14 has been announced to have the code name Forky, and Debian 15 has been announced to have the code name Duke.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian is under continuous development and new packages are uploaded to *unstable* every day.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Throughout Debian's lifetime, both the Debian distribution and its website have won various awards from different organizations, including Server Distribution of the Year 2011, The best Linux distro of 2011, and a *Best of the Net* award for October 1998.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] On December 2, 2015, Microsoft announced that they would offer Debian as an endorsed distribution on the Azure cloud platform.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian has also been made available for installation in Microsoft's Windows Subsystem for Linux, which allows a user to install a tightly integrated Debian virtual machine within Windows.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian has online repositories that contain nearly 70,000 packages for the stable release.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian officially contains only free software, but non-free software can be downloaded and installed from the Debian repositories.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian includes popular free programs such as LibreOffice, Firefox web browser, Thunderbird e-mail client, VLC media player, GIMP image editor, and Okular document viewer.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian is a popular choice for servers, for example as the operating system component of a LAMP stack.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Beyond the typical server environment, Debian is increasingly used in cloud computing, containerization, and artificial intelligence (AI) development.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] It serves as a foundation for Docker containers and is supported by Google Cloud's deep learning virtual machines (VMs), positioning it as a platform for new workloads.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Several flavors of the Linux kernel exist for each port.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] For example, the i386 port has flavors for IA-32 PCs supporting Physical Address Extension and real-time computing, for older PCs, and for x86-64 PCs.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The Linux kernel does not officially contain firmware lacking source code, although such firmware is available in non-free packages and alternative installation media.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Many desktop environments are available in the project's main repository.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] GNOME (the default in the installer) and KDE Plasma are the most widely installed according to the Debian Popularity Contest.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Other environments are also available, such as Xfce, LXDE, LXQt, MATE, and Lumina.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Standalone X11 window managers and Wayland compositors are also included, such as Openbox, Fluxbox, Compiz, awesome, i3, dwm, Notion, Sway, and wmii.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Several parts of Debian are translated into languages other than American English, including package descriptions, configuration messages, documentation and the website.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The level of software localization depends on the language, ranging from the highly supported German and French to the barely translated Creek and Samoan.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The Debian 10 installer is available in 76 languages.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Multimedia support has been problematic in Debian regarding codecs threatened by possible patent infringements, lacking source code, or under too restrictive licenses.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Even though packages with problems related to their distribution could go into the non-free area, software such as libdvdcss is not hosted at Debian .
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian offers DVD and CD images for installation that can be downloaded using HTTP, FTP, BitTorrent or jigdo.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Physical discs can also be bought from retailers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The full sets are made up of several discs (the amd64 port consists of 13 DVDs or 84 CDs), but only the first disc is required for installation, as the installer can retrieve software not contained in the first disc image from online repositories.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian offers different network installation methods.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] A minimal install of Debian is available via the *netinst* CD, whereby Debian is installed with just a base and later added software can be downloaded from the Internet.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Another option is to boot the installer from the network.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The default bootstrap loader is GNU GRUB version 2, though the package name is simply grub, while version 1 was renamed to grub-legacy.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] This conflicts with distros (e.g., Fedora Linux), where grub version 2 is named grub2.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The default desktop may be chosen from the DVD boot menu among GNOME, KDE Plasma, Xfce, LXDE, and LXQt and from special disc 1 CDs.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian releases live install images for CDs, DVDs and USB flash drives for x86-64 architecture, and with a choice of desktop environments.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] These *Debian Live* images allow users to boot from removable media and run Debian without affecting the contents of their computer.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] A full install of Debian to the computer's hard drive can be initiated from the live image environment.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Personalized images can be built with the live-build tool for discs, USB drives and for network booting purposes.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Installation images are hybrid on some architectures and can be used to create a bootable USB drive (Live USB).
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Package management operations can be performed with different tools available on Debian, from the lowest level command dpkg to graphical front-ends like Synaptic.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The recommended standard for administering packages on a Debian system is the apt toolset.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] dpkg provides the low-level infrastructure for package management.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The dpkg database contains the list of installed software on the current system.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The dpkg command tool does not know about repositories.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] These can be either under the dpkg database directory tree or in arbitrary locations specified by the user.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] An Advanced Packaging Tool (APT) allows a Debian system to retrieve and resolve package dependencies from repositories.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] APT tools share dependency information and cached packages.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] GDebi is an APT tool which can be used in command-line and on the GUI.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] GDebi can install a local .deb file via the command line like the dpkg command, but with access to repositories to resolve dependencies.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Other graphical front-ends for APT include Software Center, Synaptic and Apper.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] GNOME Software is a graphical front-end for PackageKit, which can work on various software packaging systems.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The Debian Free Software Guidelines (DFSG) define the distinctive meaning of the word "free" as in "free and open-source software".
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Packages that comply with these guidelines, usually under the GNU General Public License, Modified BSD License or Artistic License, are included inside the *main* area; otherwise, they are included inside the *non-free* and *contrib* areas.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] These last two areas are not distributed within the official installation media, but they can be adopted manually.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Non-free includes packages that do not comply with the DFSG, such as documentation with invariant sections and proprietary software, and legally questionable packages.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Contrib includes packages which do comply with the DFSG but fail other requirements.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] For example, they may depend on packages which are in non-free or requires such for building them.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Richard Stallman and the Free Software Foundation have criticized the Debian project for hosting the non-free repository and because the contrib and non-free areas are easily accessible, an opinion echoed by some in Debian including the former project leader Wichert Akkerman.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The internal dissent in the Debian project regarding the non-free section has persisted, but the last time it came to a vote in 2004, the majority voted to keep it.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The most popular optional Linux cross-distribution package manager are graphical (front-ends) package managers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] They are available within the official Debian Repository but are not installed by default.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] They are widely popular with both Debian users and Debian software developers who are interested in installing the most recent versions of application or using the cross-distribution package manager built-in sandbox environment.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] While at the same time remaining in control of the security.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The *snapshot* archive provides older versions of the branches.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] They may be used to install a specific older version of some software.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The numbering scheme for the point releases up to Debian 4.0 was to include the letter *r* (for *revision*) after the main version number and then the number of the point release; for example, the latest point release of version 4.0 is 4.0r9.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] This scheme was chosen because a new dotted version would make the old one look obsolete and vendors would have trouble selling their CDs.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] From Debian 5.0, the numbering scheme of point releases was changed, conforming to the GNU version numbering standard; the first point release of Debian 5.0 was 5.0.1 instead of 5.0r1.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The numbering scheme was once again changed for the first Debian 7 update, which was version 7.1.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The *r* scheme is no longer in use, but point release announcements include a note about not throwing away old installation media.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The official logo (also known as *open use logo*) contains the well-known Debian *swirl* and best represents the visual identity of the Debian Project.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] A separate logo also exists for use by the Debian Project and its members only.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The Debian "swirl" logo was designed by Raul Silva in 1999 as part of a contest to replace the semi-official logo that had been used.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The winner of the contest received an @Debian.org email address, and a set of Debian 2.1 install CDs for the architecture of their choice.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] There has been no official statement from the Debian project on the logo's meaning, but at the time of the logo's selection, it was suggested that the logo represented the magic smoke that made computers work.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] One theory about the origin of the Debian logo is that Buzz Lightyear, the chosen character for the first named Debian release, has a swirl in his chin.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Stefano Zacchiroli also suggested that this swirl is the Debian one.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Buzz Lightyear's swirl is a more likely candidate as the codenames for Debian are names of Toy Story characters.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The former Debian project leader Bruce Perens used to work for Pixar and is credited as a studio tools engineer on *Toy Story 2* (1999).
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Hardware requirements are at least those of the kernel and the GNU toolsets.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The real minimum memory requirements depend on the architecture and may be much less than the numbers listed in this table.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] It is possible to install Debian with 170 MB of RAM for x86-64; the installer will run in low memory mode and it is recommended to create a swap partition.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The installer for z/Architecture requires about 20 MB of RAM, but relies on network hardware.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Similarly, disk space requirements, which depend on the packages to be installed, can be reduced by manually selecting the packages needed.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] As of May 2019, no Pure Blend exists that would lower the hardware requirements easily.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] It is possible to run graphical user interfaces on older or low-end systems.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] However, installing window managers instead of desktop environments is recommended, as desktop environments use more resources.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Requirements for individual software vary widely and must be considered, with those of the base operating environment.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian supports a variety of ARM-based network-attached storage (NAS) devices.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The NSLU2 was supported by the installer in Debian 4.0 and 5.0, and Martin Michlmayr is providing installation tarballs since version 6.0.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Other supported NAS devices are the Buffalo Kurobox Pro, GLAN Tank, Thecus N2100 and QNAP Turbo Stations.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Devices based on the Kirkwood system on a chip (SoC) are supported too, such as the SheevaPlug plug computer and OpenRD products.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] There are efforts to run Debian on mobile devices, but this is not a project goal yet since the Debian Linux kernel maintainers would not apply the needed patches.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Nevertheless, packages exist for resource-limited systems.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] There are efforts to support Debian on wireless access points.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian is known to run on set-top boxes.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Work is ongoing to support the AM335x processor, which is used in electronic point of service solutions.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian may be customized to run on cash machines.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] BeagleBoard, a low-power open-source hardware single-board computer made by Texas Instruments, has switched to Debian Linux preloaded on its Beaglebone Black board's flash.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Roqos Core, a x86-64 based IPS firewall router, runs on Debian Linux.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian's policies and team efforts focus on collaborative software development and testing processes.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] As a result, a new major release tends to occur every two years with revision releases that fix security issues and important problems.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian developers are organized in a web of trust.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] There are at present about one thousand active Debian developers, but it is possible to contribute to the project without being an official developer.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The project maintains official mailing lists and conferences for communication and coordination between developers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] For issues with single packages and other tasks, a public bug tracking system is used by developers and end users.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Internet Relay Chat is also used for communication among developers and to provide real time help.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian is supported by donations made to organizations authorized by the leader.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The largest supporter is Software in the Public Interest, the owner of the Debian trademark, manager of the monetary donations and umbrella organization for various other community free software projects.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] A Project Leader is elected once per year by the developers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The leader has special powers, but they are not absolute, and appoints delegates to perform specialized tasks.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Delegates make decisions as they think is best, taking into account technical criteria and consensus.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] By way of a General Resolution, the developers may recall the leader, reverse a decision made by the leader or a delegate, amend foundation documents and make other binding decisions.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The voting method is based on the Schulze method (Cloneproof Schwartz Sequential Dropping).
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Project leadership is distributed occasionally.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Branden Robinson was helped by the Project Scud, a team of developers that assisted the leader, but there were concerns that such leadership would split Debian into two developer classes.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Anthony Towns created a supplemental position, Second In Charge (2IC), that shared some powers of the leader.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Steve McIntyre was 2IC and had a 2IC himself.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] One important role in Debian's leadership is that of a release manager.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The release team sets goals for the next release, supervises the processes and decides when to release.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The team is led by the next release managers and stable release managers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Release assistants were introduced in 2003.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The Debian Project has an influx of applicants wishing to become developers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] These applicants must undergo a vetting process which establishes their identity, motivation, understanding of the project's principles, and technical competence.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] This process has become much harder throughout the years.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian developers join the project for many reasons.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian developers may resign their position at any time, or when deemed necessary, they can be expelled.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Those who follow the retiring protocol are granted *emeritus* status and may regain their membership via a shortened new member process.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian has made efforts to diversify and have members represented from the community.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian Women in 2004 was established with the aim of having more women involved in development.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian also partnered with Outreachy, which offers internships to individuals with underrepresented identities in technology.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Each software package has a *maintainer* that may be either one person or a team of Debian developers and non-developer maintainers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The maintainer keeps track of upstream releases, and ensures that the package coheres with the rest of the distribution and meets the standards of quality of Debian.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Packages may include modifications introduced by Debian to achieve compliance with Debian Policy, even to fix non-Debian specific bugs, although coordination with upstream developers is advised.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The maintainer releases a new version by uploading the package to the "incoming" system, which verifies the integrity of the packages and their digital signatures.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] If the package is found to be valid, it is installed in the package archive into an area called the *pool* and distributed every day to hundreds of mirrors worldwide.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] As of April 5, 2025, there were a total of 379 Debian mirrors operating.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The upload must be signed using OpenPGP-compatible software.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] All Debian developers have individual cryptographic key pairs.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Developers are responsible for any package they upload even if the packaging was prepared by another contributor.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Initially, an accepted package is only available in the *unstable* branch.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Thus, a release-critical bug in a new version of a shared library on which many packages depend may prevent those packages from entering *Testing*, because the updated library must meet the requirements too.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] From the branch viewpoint, the migration process happens twice per day, rendering *Testing* in perpetual beta.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Periodically, the release team publishes guidelines to the developers in order to ready the release.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] A new release occurs after a freeze, when all important software is reasonably up-to-date in the *Testing* branch and any other significant issues are solved.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] At that time, all packages in the *testing* branch become the new *stable* branch.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Although freeze dates are time-based, release dates are not, which are announced by the release managers a couple of weeks beforehand.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] A version of a package can belong to more than one branch, usually *testing* and *unstable*.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] It is possible for a package to keep the same version between stable releases and be part of *oldstable*, *stable*, *testing* and *unstable* at the same time.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Each branch can be seen as a collection of pointers into the package "pool" mentioned above.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] One way to resolve the challenge of a release-critical bug in a new application version is the use of optional package managers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] They allow software developers to use sandbox environments, while at the same time remaining in control of security.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Another benefit of a cross-distribution package manager is that they allow application developers to directly provide updates to users without going through distributions, and without having to package and test the application separately for each distribution.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] A new *stable* branch of Debian is released about every 2 years.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] It will receive official support for about 3 years with update for major security or usability fixes.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Point releases will be available every several months as determined by Stable Release Managers (SRM).
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian also launched its Long Term Support (LTS) project since Debian 6 (Debian Squeeze).
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] For each Debian release, it will receive two years of extra security updates provided by LTS Team after its End Of Life (EOL).
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] However, no point releases will be made.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Now each Debian release can receive 5 years of security support in total.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The Debian project handles security through public disclosure.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian security advisories are compatible with the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures dictionary, are usually coordinated with other free software vendors and are published the same day a vulnerability is made public.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] There used to be a security audit project that focused on packages in the stable release looking for security bugs; Steve Kemp, who started the project, retired in 2011 but resumed his activities and applied to rejoin in 2014.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The *stable* branch is supported by the Debian security team; *oldstable* is supported for one year.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Although Squeeze was not officially supported, Debian coordinated an effort to provide long-term support for IA-32 and x86-64 platforms, until February 2016, five years after the initial release.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] *Testing* is supported by the *testing* security team, but does not receive updates in as timely a manner as *stable*.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] *Unstable*'s security is left for the package maintainers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The Debian project offers documentation and tools to harden a Debian installation both manually and automatically.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] AppArmor support is available and enabled by default since Buster.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian provides an optional hardening wrapper, and does not harden all of its software by default using gcc features such as PIE and buffer overflow protection, unlike operating systems such as OpenBSD, but tries to build as many packages as possible with hardening flags.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] In May 2008, a Debian developer discovered that the OpenSSL package distributed with Debian and derivatives such as Ubuntu made a variety of security keys vulnerable to a random number generator attack, since only 32,767 different keys were generated.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The security weakness was caused by changes made in 2006 by another Debian developer in response to memory debugger warnings.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The complete resolution procedure was cumbersome because patching the security hole was not enough; it involved regenerating all affected keys and certificates.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Recent versions of Debian have focused more on safer defaults.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian 10 had AppArmor enabled by default, and Debian 11 improved Secure Boot support and included persistent system journaling.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The project is also making all packages reproducible, which helps to ensure software integrity.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] The cost of developing all of the packages included in Debian 5.0 Lenny (323 million lines of code) has been estimated to be about US$8 billion, using one method based on the COCOMO model.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] As of May 2024, Black Duck Open Hub estimated that the current codebase (74 million lines of code) would cost about US$1.6 billion to develop, using a different method based on the same model.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian is used by several institutions, such as many universities, NGOs and other non-profit organizations (including the Wikimedia Foundation), and commercial companies.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] It has even been used in space, in laptops on board the International Space Station.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Debian has been very helpful to numerous government agencies in the public sector, such as in the city of Munich, which used a Debian-based distribution in its LiMux initiative for the government computer migration to Linux.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] Schools in Extremadura and Andalusia (Spain) also utilized Debian-based systems (gnuLinEx and Guadalinex, respectively) to develop digital skills and open-source computing in schools.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] There are many other cases of usage of Debian-based distributions in education, such as the deployment of Skolelinux/Debian Edu in Norwegian schools.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p01] In addition, other public administrations use Linux systems indirectly based on Debian, such as French Gendarmerie, which uses Ubuntu-derived GendBuntu distribution.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Debian is one of the most popular Linux distributions, and many other distributions have been created from the Debian codebase.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] As of 2025, DistroWatch lists 141 active Debian derivatives.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] The Debian project provides its derivatives with guidelines for best practices and encourages derivatives to merge their work back into Debian.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] The Linux Mint Debian Edition (LMDE) has used Debian Stable as the software source base since 2014.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Debian Pure Blends are subsets of a Debian release configured out-of-the-box for users with particular skills and interests.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] For example, Debian Jr. is made for children, while Debian Science is for researchers and scientists.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] The complete Debian distribution includes all available Debian Pure Blends.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] "Debian Blend" (without "Pure") is a term for a Debian-based distribution that strives to become part of mainstream Debian, and have its extra features included in future releases.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Debian GNU/Hurd is a flavor based on the Hurd kernel (which, in turn, runs on the GNU Mach microkernel), instead of the Linux kernel.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Debian GNU/Hurd has been in development since 1998, and made a formal release in May 2013, with 78% of the software packaged for Debian ported to the GNU Hurd.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Hurd is not yet an official Debian release, and is maintained and developed as an unofficial port.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Debian GNU/Hurd is distributed as an installer CD (running the official Debian installer) or ready-to-run virtual disk image (Live CD, Live USB).
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] The CD uses the IA-32 architecture, making it compatible with IA-32 and x86-64 PCs.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] The current version of Debian GNU/Hurd is 2025, published in August 2025.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Debian GNU/kFreeBSD is a discontinued Debian flavor.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] It used the FreeBSD kernel and GNU userland.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] The majority of software in Debian GNU/kFreeBSD was built from the same sources as Debian, with some kernel packages from FreeBSD.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] The *k* in *kFreeBSD* is an abbreviation for *kernel*, which refers to the FreeBSD kernel.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Before discontinuing the project, Debian maintained i386 and amd64 ports.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] The last version of Debian kFreeBSD was Debian 8 (Jessie) RC3.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Debian GNU/kFreeBSD was created in 2002.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] It was included in Debian 6.0 (Squeeze) as a technology preview, and in Debian 7 (Wheezy) as an official port.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Debian GNU/kFreeBSD was discontinued as an officially supported platform as of Debian 8.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] Debian developers cited OSS, pf, jails, NDIS, and ZFS as reasons for being interested in the FreeBSD kernel.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] It has not been officially updated since Debian 8.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] However, starting in July 2019, the operating system continued to be maintained unofficially.
[src:debian-linux/debian-p02] As of July 2023, the development of Debian GNU/kFreeBSD has officially terminated due to the lack of interest and developers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian releases do not follow a fixed schedule.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Recent releases have been made around every two years by the Debian Project.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The most recent version of Debian is Debian version 13, codename "Trixie".
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The next up and coming release of Debian is Debian 14, codename "Forky".
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian always has at least three active branches at any time: "stable", "testing" and "unstable".
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The stable branch is considered the primary release and what most people refer to when talking about Debian.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The testing branch contains packages that have been imported from unstable.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Testing has significantly more up-to-date packages than stable and is frozen some time before a release to become the next version of Debian.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The unstable release (also known as Sid) is the branch where active development takes place.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] It is the most volatile version of Debian.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] When the Debian stable branch is replaced with a newer release, the current stable becomes an "oldstable" release.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] When the Debian stable branch is replaced again, the oldstable release becomes the "oldoldstable" release.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Oldoldstable is eventually moved to the archived releases repository.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian distribution codenames are based on the names of characters from the *Toy Story* films.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian's *unstable* branch is named after Sid, a character who regularly destroyed his toys.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian Unstable, known as "Sid", contains all the latest packages as soon as they are available, and follows a rolling-release model.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Once a package has been in Debian Unstable for 2–10 days (depending on the urgency of the upload), doesn't introduce critical bugs and doesn't break other packages (among other conditions), it is included in Debian Testing, also known as "next-stable".
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] On average about every two years, Debian Testing enters a "freeze" cycle, where new packages are held back unless they fix critical bugs.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] This frozen state lasts on average 7 months (but can be as short as one month).
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Once Debian Testing doesn't contain any more release critical bugs, it is declared "stable" and released with a version number.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Extended long-term support (ELTS) is provided by Freexian to subscribers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] There is no kernel support, and only sponsored packages are supported.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Only 7 are candidates for stable releases.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] When a release transitions to long-term support phase (LTS-phase), security is no longer handled by the main Debian security team.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Only a subset of Debian architectures are eligible for Long Term Support, and there is no support for packages in backports.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian had fully transitioned to the ELF binary format and used Linux kernel 2.0.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 1.2 (*Rex*), released 12 December 1996, contained 848 packages maintained by 120 developers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 1.3 (*Bo*), released 5 June 1997, contained 974 packages maintained by 200 developers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 2.0 (*Hamm*), released 24 July 1998, contained over 1,500 packages maintained by over 400 developers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] A transition was made to libc6 and Debian was ported to the Motorola 68000 series (m68k) architectures.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 2.1 (*Slink*), released 9 March 1999, contained about 2,250 packages.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The front-end APT was introduced for the package management system and Debian was ported to Alpha and SPARC.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 2.2 (*Potato*), released 14–15 August 2000, contained 2,600 packages maintained by more than 450 developers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] New packages included the display manager GDM, the directory service OpenLDAP, the security software OpenSSH and the mail transfer agent Postfix.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian was ported to the PowerPC and ARM architectures.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 3.0 (*Woody*), released 19 July 2002, contained around 8,500 packages maintained by more than 900 developers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] KDE was introduced and Debian was ported to the following architectures: IA-64, PA-RISC (hppa), mips and mipsel and IBM ESA/390 (s390).
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 3.1 (*Sarge*), released 6 June 2005, contained around 15,400 packages. debian-installer, OpenOffice.org and GNOME 2.8 were introduced.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 4.0 (*Etch*), released 8 April 2007, contained around 18,000 packages maintained by more than 1,030 developers.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian was ported to x86-64 (amd64) and support for the Motorola 68000 series (m68k) architecture was dropped.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] This version introduced UTF-8 and udev device management by default.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 5.0 (*Lenny*), released 14 February 2009, contained more than 23,000 packages.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian was ported to the ARM EABI (armel) architecture.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 6.0 (*Squeeze*), released 6 February 2011, contained more than 29,000 packages.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The default Linux kernel included was deblobbed beginning with this release.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The web browser Chromium was introduced and Debian was ported to the kfreebsd-i386 and kfreebsd-amd64 architectures (while that port was later discontinued), and support for the Intel 486, Alpha, and PA-RISC (hppa) architectures was dropped.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Squeeze was the first release of Debian in which non-free firmware components (aka "binary blobs") were excluded from the "main" repository as a matter of policy.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 7 (*Wheezy*), released 4 May 2013, contained more than 36,000 packages.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Support for UEFI was added and Debian was ported to the armhf and IBM z/Architecture (s390x) architectures.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 8 (*Jessie*), released 25 April 2015, contained more than 43,000 packages, with systemd installed by default instead of init.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 9 (Stretch) was released on 17 June 2017, two years and two months after Debian 8.0, and contained more than 51,000 packages.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The final minor update, called a "point release", is version 9.13, released on 18 July 2020 (2020-07-18).
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Major upgrades include the Linux kernel going from version 3.16 to 4.9, GNOME desktop version going from 3.14 to 3.22, KDE Plasma 4 was upgraded to Plasma 5, LibreOffice 4.3 upgraded to 5.2 and Qt upgraded from 4.8 to 5.7.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The Intel i586 (Pentium), i586/i686 hybrid and PowerPC architectures are no longer supported as of Stretch.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] It was two years and a month after Debian 9 (Stretch).
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 10 contains 57,703 packages, supports UEFI Secure Boot, has AppArmor enabled by default, uses LUKS2 as the default LUKS format, and uses Wayland for GNOME by default.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 10 ships with Linux kernel version 4.19.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Key application software includes LibreOffice 6.1 for office productivity, VLC 3.0 for media viewing, and Firefox ESR for web browsing.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 11 (Bullseye) was released on 14 August 2021.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] It is based on the Linux 5.10 LTS kernel and will be supported for five years.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] On 12 November 2020, it was announced that "Homeworld", by Juliette Taka, will be the default theme for Debian 11, after winning a public poll held with eighteen choices.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Bullseye dropped the remaining Qt4/KDE 4 libraries and Python 2, and shipped with Qt 5.15 KDE Plasma 5.20.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Available desktops include Gnome 3.38, KDE Plasma 5.20, LXDE 11, LXQt 0.16, MATE 1.24, and Xfce 4.16.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Bullseye does not support the older big-endian 32-bit MIPS architectures.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] The first of the code freezes, readying Debian 11 for release, began on 12 January 2021.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 12 (Bookworm) was released on 10 June 2023.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] It is based on Linux kernel v6.1 LTS, and uses GNOME 43 as its default desktop environment, but as usual many other desktops are available, such as KDE Plasma 5.27, LXDE 11, LXQt 1.2.0, MATE 1.26, and Xfce 4.18.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Bookworm raised the compatibility level of its 32 bit x86 PC port from i586 to i686 compatibility.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 12 (Bookworm) is the last version of Debian with KDE Plasma 5.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] A change was also made to the Debian Social Contract to allow for this change to be made.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 13, codenamed Trixie, was released 9 August 2025.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 13 adds support for 64 bit RISC-V.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian 13 drops support for the mipsel architecture, and drops the installers for the i386 (all 32-bit x86 CPUs) and armel architectures.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Debian directs users to keep i386 systems on Debian 12 or retiring the system in question, as the remaining packages are intended for running 32-bit x86 software on 64-bit systems and require the SSE2 CPU instruction set that most 32-bit x86 CPUs don't support.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Following the release of Debian 13 (Trixie) on 9 August 2025, testing is known by the codename Forky which is anticipated to be released as Debian 14 in 2027.
[src:debian-linux/debian-version-history] Many of past architectures, plus some that have not yet achieved release status, are available from the *debian-ports* repository.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] `dpkg` (Debian Package) itself is a low-level tool.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] Advanced Package Tool (APT), a higher-level tool, is more commonly used than `dpkg` as it can fetch packages from remote locations and deal with complex package relations, such as dependency resolution.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] Frontends for APT, like aptitude (ncurses) and synaptic (GTK), are used for their user-friendly interfaces.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] The Debian package *dpkg* provides the `dpkg` program, and several other programs needed for runtime functioning of the packaging system, including `dpkg-deb`, `dpkg-split`, `dpkg-query`, `dpkg-statoverride`, `dpkg-divert` and `dpkg-trigger`.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] It also includes the programs such as `update-alternatives` and `start-stop-daemon`.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] The Debian package "dpkg-dev" includes the many build tools described below.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] The first attempt at a package management system for Linux was possibly the development of StopAlop by Greg Wettstein at the Roger Maris Cancer Center in Fargo, North Dakota.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] It provided inspiration to create dpkg. dpkg was originally created by Ian Murdock in January 1994 as a Shell script.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] Matt Welsh, Carl Streeter and Ian Murdock then rewrote it in Perl, and then later the main part was rewritten in C by Ian Jackson in 1994.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] The name *dpkg* was originally a shortening of *Debian package*, but the meaning of that phrase has evolved significantly, as dpkg the software is orthogonal to the deb package format and the Debian Policy Manual which defines how Debian packages behave in Debian.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] dpkg-dev contains a series of development tools needed to unpack, build, and upload Debian source code packages.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] The dpkg source package also contains *dselect*, a frontend software.
[src:debian-linux/dpkg] The `install-info` program used to be included in the dpkg software package, but was later removed as it became developed and distributed separately, as part of GNU Texinfo.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] A **Linux distribution**, often abbreviated as **distro**, is an operating system that includes the Linux kernel for its kernel functionality.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Although the name does not imply product distribution per se, a distro—if distributed on its own—is often obtained via a website intended specifically for the purpose.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Distros have been designed for a wide variety of systems ranging from personal computers (for example, Linux Mint and Zorin OS) to servers (for example, Red Hat Enterprise Linux) and from embedded devices (for example, OpenWrt) to supercomputers (for example, Rocks Cluster Distribution).
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] A distro typically includes many components in addition to the Linux kernel.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Commonly, it includes a package manager, an init system (such as systemd, OpenRC, SysVinit, or runit), GNU tools and libraries, documentation, IP network configuration utilities, the getty TTY setup program, and many more.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Typically, most of the included software is free and open-source software – made available both as binary for convenience and as source code to allow for modifying it.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] A distro may also include proprietary software that is not available in source code form, such as a device driver binary.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] A distro may be described as a particular assortment of application and utility software (various GNU tools and libraries, for example), packaged with the Linux kernel in such a way that its capabilities meet users' needs.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The software is usually adapted to the distribution and then combined into software packages by the distribution's maintainers.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The software packages are available online in repositories, which are storage locations usually distributed around the world.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Beside "glue" components, such as the distribution installers (for example, Debian-Installer and Anaconda) and the package management systems, very few packages are actually written by a distribution's maintainers.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Distributions have been designed for a wide range of computing environments, including desktops, servers, laptops, netbooks, mobile devices (phones and tablets), and embedded systems.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] There are commercially backed distributions, such as Red Hat Enterprise Linux (Red Hat), openSUSE (SUSE) and Ubuntu (Canonical), and entirely community-driven distributions, such as Debian, Slackware, Gentoo and Arch Linux.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Most distributions come ready-to-use and prebuilt for a specific instruction set, while some (such as Gentoo) are distributed mostly in source code form and must be built before installation.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Linus Torvalds developed the Linux kernel and distributed its first version, 0.01, in 1991.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Linux was initially distributed as source code only, and later as a pair of downloadable floppy disk images: one bootable and containing the Linux kernel itself, and the other with a set of GNU utilities and tools for setting up a file system.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Since the installation procedure was complicated, especially in the face of growing amounts of available software, distributions sprang up to simplify it.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The two oldest, still active distribution projects started in 1993.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The SLS distribution was not well maintained, so in July 1993 a new SLS-based distribution, Slackware, was released by Patrick Volkerding.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Also dissatisfied with SLS, Ian Murdock set to create a free distribution by founding Debian in August 1993, with first public BETA released in January 1994 and first stable version in June 1996.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Users were attracted to Linux distributions as alternatives to MS-DOS compatible operating systems, Windows, Classic Mac OS, and proprietary versions of Unix.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Most early adopters were familiar with Unix from work or school.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] They embraced Linux distributions for their low (or absent) cost, and the availability of the source code for most or all of their software.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] As of 2025, Linux has become more popular in server and embedded devices markets than in the desktop market.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] It is used in approximately 64.5% of web servers; its current operating system market share is about 2.51%, and its desktop operating system market share is about 2.94%.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide an installation system akin to that provided with other modern operating systems.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Other distributions, including Gentoo Linux, provide only the binaries of a basic kernel, compilation tools, and an installer; the installer compiles all the requested software for the specific architecture of the user's computer, using these tools and the software's source code.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Distributions are normally segmented into *packages*.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Each package contains a specific application or service.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Examples of packages are a library for handling the PNG image format, a collection of fonts, and a web browser.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The package is typically provided as compiled code, with installation and removal of packages handled by a package management system (PMS) rather than a simple file archiver.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Each package intended for such a PMS contains meta-information such as its description, version number, and its dependencies (other packages it requires to run).
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The package management system evaluates this meta-information to allow package searches, perform automatic upgrades to newer versions, and to check that all dependencies of a package are present (and either notify the user to install them, or install them automatically).
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The package can also be provided as source code to be compiled on the system.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Most distributions install packages, including the kernel and other core operating system components, in a predetermined configuration.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] A few now require or permit configuration adjustments at first install time.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] This makes installation less daunting, particularly for new users, but is not always acceptable.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] For specific requirements, much software must be carefully configured to be useful, to work correctly with other software, or to be secure, and local administrators are often obliged to spend time reviewing and reconfiguring it.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Some (but not all) distributions go to considerable lengths to adjust and customize the software they include, and some provide configuration tools to help users do so.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] By obtaining and installing *everything* normally provided in a distribution, an administrator may create a "distribution less" installation.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] It is possible to build such systems from scratch, avoiding distributions altogether.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] One needs a way to generate the first binaries until the system is *self-hosting*.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] This can be done via compilation on another system capable of building binaries for the intended target (possibly by cross-compilation).
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions is due to technical, organizational, and philosophical variation among vendors and users.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The permissive licensing of free software means that users with sufficient knowledge and interest can customize any extant distribution, or design one to suit their own needs.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Rolling Linux distributions are kept current using small and frequent updates.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The terms *partially rolling* and *partly rolling* (along with synonyms *semi-rolling* and *half-rolling*), *fully rolling*, *truly rolling* and *optionally rolling* are sometimes used by software developers and users.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Repositories of **rolling distributions** usually contain very recent software releases—often the latest stable versions available.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] They have pseudo-releases and installation media that are simply snapshots of the distribution at the time of the installation image's release.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Typically, a rolling-release OS installed from older installation medium can be fully updated after it is installed.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Depending on the usage case, there can be pros and cons to both standard release and rolling release software development methodologies.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] In terms of the software development process, **standard releases** require significant development effort to keep old versions up-to-date by propagating bug fixes back to the newest branch, versus focusing on the newest development branch.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Also, unlike rolling releases, standard releases require more than one code branch to be developed and maintained, which increases the workload of the software developers and maintainers.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] On the other hand, software features and technology planning are easier in standard releases due to a better understanding of upcoming features in the next version(s).
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Software release cycles can also be synchronized with those of major upstream software projects, such as desktop environments.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] As for the user experience, standard releases are often viewed as more stable and bug-free since software conflicts can be more easily addressed and the software stack more thoroughly tested and evaluated, during the software development cycle.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] For this reason, they tend to be the preferred choice in enterprise environments and mission-critical tasks.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] However, rolling releases offer more current software which can also provide increased stability and fewer software bugs along with the additional benefits of new features, greater functionality, faster running speeds, and improved system and application security.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Regarding software security, the rolling release model can have advantages in timely security updates, fixing system or application security bugs and vulnerabilities, that standard releases may have to wait till the next release for or patch in various versions.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] In a rolling release distribution, where the user has chosen to run it as a highly dynamic system, the constant flux of software packages can introduce new unintended vulnerabilities.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] A "live" distribution is a Linux distribution that can be booted from removable storage media such as optical discs or USB flash drives, instead of being installed on and booted from a hard disk drive.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The portability of installation-free distributions makes them advantageous for applications such as demonstrations, borrowing someone else's computer, rescue operations, or as installation media for a standard distribution.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] When the operating system is booted from a read-only medium such as a CD or DVD, any user data that needs to be retained between sessions cannot be stored on the boot device but must be written to another storage device, such as a USB flash drive or a hard disk drive.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Many Linux distributions provide a "live" form in addition to their conventional form, which is a network-based or removable-media image intended to be used only for installation; such distributions include antiX, SUSE, Ubuntu, Linux Mint, MX Linux and Fedora Linux.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions, including Knoppix, Puppy Linux, Devil-Linux, SuperGamer, SliTaz GNU/Linux and dyne:bolic, are designed primarily for live use.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Additionally, some minimal distributions can be run directly from as little space as one floppy disk without the need to change the contents of the system's hard disk drive.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The website DistroWatch lists many Linux distributions and displays some of the ones that have the most web traffic on the site.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The Wikimedia Foundation released an analysis of the browser User Agents of visitors to WMF websites until 2015, which includes details of the most popular Operating System identifiers, including some Linux distributions.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Many of the popular distributions are listed below.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Whether such operating systems count as a "Linux distribution" is a controversial topic.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] They use the Linux kernel, so the Linux Foundation and Chris DiBona, Google's former open-source chief, agree that Android is a Linux distribution; others, such as Google engineer Patrick Brady, disagree by noting the lack of support for many GNU tools in Android, including glibc.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Other Linux-kernel-based operating systems include Tizen, Mer/Sailfish OS, KaiOS and Amazon's Kindle firmware.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Lightweight Linux distributions are those that have been designed with support for older hardware in mind, allowing older hardware to still be used productively, or, for maximum possible speed in newer hardware by leaving more resources available for use by applications.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Examples include antiX, Damn Small Linux (based on antiX), Tiny Core Linux, Puppy Linux and Slitaz.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The Free Standards Group was an organization formed by major software and hardware vendors that aims to improve interoperability between different distributions.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Among their proposed standards are the Linux Standard Base, which defines a common ABI and packaging system for Linux, and the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard which recommends a standard file naming chart, notably the basic directory names found on the root of the tree of any Linux filesystem.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Those standards, however, see limited use, even among the distributions developed by members of the organization.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The diversity of Linux distributions means that not all software runs on all distributions, depending on what libraries and other system attributes are required.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Packaged software and software repositories are usually specific to a particular distribution, though cross-installation is sometimes possible on closely related distributions.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] One of solutions for interdistribution issues, particularly to run software created for a distribution on another, is by using container such as Distrobox.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] There are several ways to install a Linux distribution.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The most popular method of installing Linux is by booting from a live USB memory stick, which can be created by using a USB image writer application and the ISO image, which can be downloaded from various Linux distribution websites.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] DVD disks, CD disks, network installations and even other hard drives can also be used as "installation media".
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] In the 1990s, Linux distributions were installed using sets of floppy disks, but this has been abandoned by all major distributions.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] By the 2000s, many distributions offered CD and DVD sets with the vital packages on the first disk and less important packages on later ones.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions, such as Debian also enabled installing over a network after booting from either a set of floppy disks or a CD with only a small amount of data on it.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] New users tend to begin by partitioning a hard drive to keep their formerly installed operating system.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The Linux distribution can then be installed on its own separate partition without affecting formerly saved data.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] In a Live CD setup, the computer boots the entire operating system from CD without first installing it on the computer's hard disk.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Many distributions have a Live CD *installer*, where the computer boots the operating system from the disk, and it can then be installed on the computer's hard disk, providing a seamless transition from the OS running from the CD to the OS running from the hard disk.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Both servers and personal computers that come with Linux already installed are available from vendors including Hewlett-Packard, Dell and System76.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] On embedded devices, Linux is typically held in the device's firmware and may or may not be consumer-accessible.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Anaconda, one of the more popular installers, is used by Red Hat Enterprise Linux, Fedora (which uses the Fedora Media Writer) and other distributions to simplify the installation process.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Debian, Ubuntu and many others use Debian-Installer.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The process of constantly switching between distributions is often referred to as "distro hopping".
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Virtual machine software such as VirtualBox and VMware Workstation virtualize hardware allowing users to test live media on a virtual machine without installing to the real system.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Some websites like DistroWatch offer lists of distributions, and link to screenshots of operating systems as a way to get a first impression of various distributions.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Some distributions let the user install Linux on top of their current system, such as coLinux.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Linux is installed to the Windows hard disk partition, and can be started from inside Windows itself.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Virtual machines (such as VirtualBox or VMware Workstation) also make it possible for Linux to be run inside another OS.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The VM software simulates a separate computer onto which the Linux system is installed.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] After installation, the virtual machine can be booted as if it were an independent computer.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Some specific proprietary software products are not available in any form for Linux.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] As of September 2015, the Steam gaming service has over 1,500 games available on Linux, compared to 2,323 games for Mac and 6,500 Windows games.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Emulation and API-translation projects like Wine and CrossOver make it possible to run non-Linux-based software on Linux systems, either by emulating a proprietary operating system or by translating proprietary API calls (e.g., calls to Microsoft's Win32 or DirectX APIs) into native Linux API calls.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] A virtual machine can also be used to run a proprietary OS (like Microsoft Windows) on top of Linux.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Pre-built computers are usually sold with an operating system other than Linux already installed by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] This limits Linux's market share: consumers are unaware that an alternative exists, they must make a conscious effort to use a different operating system, and they must either perform the actual installation themselves, or depend on support from a friend, relative, or computer professional.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] However, it is possible to buy hardware with Linux already installed.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Lenovo, Hewlett-Packard, Dell, Affordy, Purism, Pine64 and System76 all sell general-purpose Linux laptops.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Custom-order PC manufacturers will also build Linux systems, but possibly with the Windows key on the keyboard.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Fixstars Solutions (formerly Terra Soft) sold Macintosh computers and PlayStation 3 consoles with Yellow Dog Linux installed.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] It is more common to find embedded devices sold with Linux as the default manufacturer-supported OS, including the Linksys NSLU2 NAS device, TiVo's line of personal video recorders, and Linux-based cellphones (including Android smartphones), PDAs, and portable music players.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] The current Microsoft Windows license lets the manufacturer determine the refund policy.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] With prior versions of Windows, it was possible to obtain a refund if the manufacturer failed to provide the refund by litigation in the small claims courts.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] On February 15, 1999, a group of Linux users in Orange County, California held a "Windows Refund Day" protest in an attempt to pressure Microsoft into issuing them refunds.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] There are no official figures on the popularity, adoption, downloads or installed base of Linux distributions.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] There are also no official figures for the total number of Linux systems, partly due to the difficulty of quantifying the number of PCs running Linux (see Desktop Linux adoption), since many users download Linux distributions.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Hence, the sales figures for Linux systems and commercial Linux distributions indicate a much lower number of Linux systems and level of Linux adoption than is the case; this is mainly due to Linux being free and open-source software that can be downloaded free of charge.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] A Linux Counter Project had kept track of a running guesstimate of the number of Linux systems, but did not distinguish between rolling release and standard release distributions.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] It ceased operation in August 2018, though a few related blog posts were created through October 2018.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Desktop usage statistical reports for particular Linux distributions have been collected and published since July 2014 by the Linux Hardware Project.
[src:debian-linux/linux-distribution] Statcounter, a web traffic analysis company, within the *operating system market share*, showed that the Linux operating systems had, according to them, 3.9% of the worldwide market share in July 2025.
